SIMPLE: exhale
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exhale
<hw>Ex*hale"</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧ks*h⟦amac⟧l" or ⟦ecr⟧gz*⟦amac⟧l")</pr>,
<pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Exaled</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>.
<conjf>Exaling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>exhalare</ets>;
<ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>halare</ets> to breathe; cf.F.
<ets>exhaler</ets>. Cf. <er>Inhale</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
breathe out. Hence: To emit, as vapor; to send out, as an odor; to
evaporate; <as>as, the earth <ex>exhales</ex> vapor; marshes
<ex>exhale</ex> noxious effluvia.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Less fragrant scents the unfolding rose <qex>exhales</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw out; to cause to be emitted in vapor;
<as>as, the sun <ex>exhales</ex> the moisture of the
earth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exhale</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Exhale
<hw>Ex*hale"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To rise or be given off, as
vapor; to pass off, or vanish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their inspiration <qex>exhaled</qex> in elegies.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exhalement</ent>⟦br⟧
